  footnotes: []
english:
  title: An Edict Refusing Gwon Jun's Declining of the Position of Vice Director of the Bureau of Secrets
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your office brings you near the throne—thus it is called the Central Bureau. Your rank stands equal to the highest ministers—thus it is named the Twin Pillars. The burden of such station is grave indeed, and worthy men are scarce as precious jade.

    You possess both depth of character and brilliance of spirit. Early favored by fortune's examination, you have served in many positions of trust and influence. In the Censorate, your authority gleamed with the severity of winter frost, your rebukes sharp and just. In the Ministry of Personnel, your judgments shone like a mirror's reflection, fair and impartial in all selections. Serving in military affairs abroad, you brought honor to our armies. Considering your accumulated merit, advancement should rightfully come.

    Moreover, your grandfather moved the very heart of China through his literary genius—his fragrant legacy endures still. Your father, spurning rank and fortune, dwells peacefully in his garden retreat—such noble restraint commands our admiration. It is certain his descendants shall rise greatly. Who better than you to fulfill this destiny?

    Though your present post carries weight in the outer councils, your position remains somewhat removed from the inner circle. Thus we elevate you to the Bureau of Secrets, to demonstrate our favor. Yet you demur in modesty. But tell me—who else could fill this role?
  footnotes:
    - The 'Twin Pillars' (兩府) refers to the highest administrative bodies—this position places one among the empire's most senior officials
    - The 'winter frost' imagery refers to the Censorate's function as stern moral guardian of the court
    - The reference to the grandfather's literary achievements and the father's virtuous withdrawal suggests this family represents the Confucian ideal of both service and moral integrity
